00:01:16.944 --> 00:01:18.750
And now, here's John Udell.

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:21.748
Jon: I saw something
online the other evening

00:01:21.748 --> 00:01:23.244
that reminded me of what you're doing

00:01:23.244 --> 00:01:25.750
in an interesting way, so it might be

00:01:25.750 --> 00:01:26.742
a fun place to start.

00:01:26.742 --> 00:01:30.420
There's an artist in Los Angeles named

00:01:30.420 --> 00:01:33.300
Richard Ankrom and somewhere around

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:36.661
2000 or 2001, he got pissed
off about the fact that

00:01:36.661 --> 00:01:39.842
there's this freeway
intersection in Los Angeles

00:01:39.842 --> 00:01:42.163
that's very poorly labeled.

00:01:42.163 --> 00:01:44.343
In particular, there
was a key missing piece

00:01:44.343 --> 00:01:46.343
of information which was a place where

00:01:46.343 --> 00:01:49.164
there should have been a
sign that said "North 5".

00:01:49.164 --> 00:01:51.333
It just wasn't there.

00:01:51.333 --> 00:01:57.581
(laughs) So he went and
made a "North 5" sign

00:01:57.581 --> 00:02:00.844
to the Highway Department's
specifications,

00:02:00.844 --> 00:02:03.443
then he made himself a uniform,

00:02:03.443 --> 00:02:04.938
then he got up on a ladder and

00:02:04.938 --> 00:02:06.748
he went out and he installed the thing.

00:02:06.748 --> 00:02:10.820
(laughter)

00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:13.044
He calls this "Gorilla
Public Service" as in

00:02:13.044 --> 00:02:14.577
"Gorilla the Freedom Fighter", not

00:02:14.577 --> 00:02:17.243
"Gorilla the Great Ape",

00:02:17.243 --> 00:02:20.332
and since then, as far
as I know, it's still up

00:02:20.332 --> 00:02:23.500
and probably millions of
people have benefited from that

00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:26.495
and it just reminded
me of what you're doing

00:02:26.495 --> 00:02:29.544
in a way, in the realm
of education which is

00:02:29.544 --> 00:02:31.832
sort of looking at a
situation and thinking,

00:02:31.832 --> 00:02:32.998
"You know what? I'm just going to go do

00:02:32.998 --> 00:02:34.943
something about that."

00:02:34.943 --> 00:02:38.344
Thanks to the technology of the internet,

00:02:38.344 --> 00:02:40.282
I can be a super empowered individual,

00:02:40.282 --> 00:02:42.707
and there really is essentially no limit

00:02:42.707 --> 00:02:44.433
to how far that can scale out and

00:02:44.433 --> 00:02:46.784
how many people I can help.

00:02:46.784 --> 00:02:48.737
It's really a wonderful thing.

00:02:48.737 --> 00:02:52.335
So tell us about the Kahn Academy.

00:02:52.335 --> 00:02:57.541
Sal: It's most known for the
roughly 1,200 videos on YouTube.

00:02:57.541 --> 00:02:59.364
It's being aired other places and

00:02:59.364 --> 00:03:01.522
other people are distributing it offline,

00:03:01.522 --> 00:03:03.950
but YouTube's really the main way that

00:03:03.950 --> 00:03:05.865
people access the videos.

00:03:05.865 --> 00:03:09.952
It really started off very organically and

00:03:09.952 --> 00:03:12.537
I was helping cousins
and family members and

00:03:12.537 --> 00:03:14.861
it seemed to be working well.

00:03:14.861 --> 00:03:16.135
I was tutoring them remotely.

00:03:16.135 --> 00:03:18.837
I was in Boston, I'm in
Northern California now,

00:03:18.837 --> 00:03:21.828
but they were in New Orleans.

00:03:21.828 --> 00:03:23.537
When I was doing this
one-on-one tutoring with them,

00:03:23.537 --> 00:03:24.737
it seemed to be very effective.

00:03:24.737 --> 00:03:26.638
I just kept thinking of
how could I make it scale.

00:03:26.638 --> 00:03:29.037
There's actually a software piece that

00:03:29.037 --> 00:03:30.786
I started working on at first and

00:03:30.786 --> 00:03:31.371
a buddy of mine said,

00:03:31.371 --> 00:03:34.337
"Why don't you put some
videos in the software?"

00:03:34.337 --> 00:03:35.538
By the time I got over the idea that

00:03:35.538 --> 00:03:38.836
I didn't think of it
(laughs), I started recording

00:03:38.836 --> 00:03:42.536
a couple of videos and the
videos are what really took off.

00:03:42.536 --> 00:03:44.340
I think it's just the
low barrier for people

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:46.128
to use it, even my own cousins say that

00:03:46.128 --> 00:03:47.836
I'm better on YouTube than I am live.

00:03:47.836 --> 00:03:49.197
Jon: (laughs)

00:03:49.197 --> 00:03:51.540
Sal: Pause and repeat
me and they don't like

00:03:51.540 --> 00:03:55.035
the video's judging them
the way I (laughs) ...

00:03:55.035 --> 00:03:59.927
I put it out there and I think as a fellow

00:03:59.927 --> 00:04:02.537
software engineer, you can
appreciate how fun it is

00:04:02.537 --> 00:04:04.418
when people actually
use something you built.

00:04:04.418 --> 00:04:06.451
When I just put it out there,

00:04:06.451 --> 00:04:08.521
I've written hundreds of
pieces of software that

00:04:08.521 --> 00:04:11.330
absolutely no one uses
and just put a couple

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:12.865
YouTube videos out there and within a day,

00:04:12.865 --> 00:04:14.785
at least when I started,
20 or 30 people were

00:04:14.785 --> 00:04:18.036
using them and some of them
would write notes saying,

00:04:18.036 --> 00:04:20.277
"I got an A on my Algebra
exam because of this," or

00:04:20.277 --> 00:04:24.370
"I feel prepared to go
back to college next year."

00:04:24.370 --> 00:04:25.781
Some of them were, "I
was going to drop out

00:04:25.781 --> 00:04:27.835
until I saw something like this," so

00:04:27.835 --> 00:04:29.136
you just get one note
like that, you're like,

00:04:29.136 --> 00:04:30.927
"This has more impact than I've ever had

00:04:30.927 --> 00:04:32.698
doing anything else!" so I just kept

00:04:32.698 --> 00:04:35.635
making the videos and
the traffic just kept

00:04:35.635 --> 00:04:38.736
picking up organically
and it started to become

00:04:38.736 --> 00:04:41.635
pretty clear that there
was a need being addressed.

00:04:41.635 --> 00:04:45.138
Jon: So you've actually decided
to try to reconfigure your life,

00:04:45.138 --> 00:04:48.350
or you have reconfigured
your life around this,

00:04:48.350 --> 00:04:51.205
away from most recently,
financial services?

00:04:51.205 --> 00:04:54.138
Sal: Yeah. When I first
started doing this,

00:04:54.138 --> 00:04:56.335
I was originally tutoring my cousin Nadia

00:04:56.335 --> 00:04:58.279
in New Orleans, they had just visited me

00:04:58.279 --> 00:04:59.340
in Boston after my wedding.

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:02.036
I was a hedge fund analyst in Boston and

00:05:02.036 --> 00:05:04.696
I was a hedge fund analyst until this past

00:05:04.696 --> 00:05:10.325
September and while my
day job was in finance,

00:05:10.325 --> 00:05:12.952
I had already reconfigured
my life around this.

00:05:12.952 --> 00:05:15.517
Pretty much every waking
moment where I felt that

00:05:15.517 --> 00:05:17.225
my wife wouldn't feel that I was being

00:05:17.225 --> 00:05:19.367
completely delinquent of my family duties,

00:05:19.367 --> 00:05:22.335
I would sneak away and
start doing YouTube videos.

00:05:22.335 --> 00:05:23.637
I'd also work on the software that would

00:05:23.637 --> 00:05:26.370
give people exercises
to do so I could track

00:05:26.370 --> 00:05:29.400
what they were doing.

00:05:29.400 --> 00:05:32.322
I've kind of just come to
terms with the fact that

00:05:32.322 --> 00:05:34.537
this is what I think I
should be doing all the time

00:05:34.537 --> 00:05:36.436
so in September I quit
my job and I've been

00:05:36.436 --> 00:05:39.131
doing it full time, and I
haven't looked back since,

00:05:39.131 --> 00:05:43.350
although my bank account
is slowly depleting,

00:05:43.350 --> 00:05:44.434
so hopefully I'll figure out a way to

00:05:44.434 --> 00:05:47.371
make that at least a "not deplete".

00:05:47.371 --> 00:05:50.367
Jon: I am certain that you will and

00:05:50.367 --> 00:05:53.287
I hope that people who
will be listening to this

00:05:53.287 --> 00:05:55.945
can maybe help with that because this is

00:05:55.945 --> 00:05:58.227
clearly what you should be spending your

00:05:58.227 --> 00:06:00.195
time doing and I think
you've written somewhere

00:06:00.195 --> 00:06:03.106
that you realized this
was the way you could

00:06:03.106 --> 00:06:06.036
have the most leverage
and do the most good

00:06:06.036 --> 00:06:07.356
and have the most fun.

00:06:07.356 --> 00:06:09.281
Sal: Oh yeah! Just think about it ...

00:06:09.281 --> 00:06:13.931
It's such a simple thing,
I could do a video on

00:06:13.931 --> 00:06:15.828
the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus and

00:06:15.828 --> 00:06:19.036
it might take me maybe if it's something

00:06:19.036 --> 00:06:20.943
I knew before I even started doing this,

00:06:20.943 --> 00:06:22.529
I don't have to prepare much and

00:06:22.529 --> 00:06:24.221
it takes me 10 or 20
minutes to do the video

00:06:24.221 --> 00:06:25.837
and I put it up there.

00:06:25.837 --> 00:06:28.436
Literally millions of people,

00:06:28.436 --> 00:06:29.734
for as long as the internet exists,

00:06:29.734 --> 00:06:32.137
can use that video.

00:06:32.137 --> 00:06:34.734
My or your great grandchildren
could use that video

00:06:34.734 --> 00:06:38.109
so just in terms of the
return on time invested

00:06:38.109 --> 00:06:40.946
or the return on mental capital invested,

00:06:40.946 --> 00:06:43.135
however you want to view
it, is mind-boggling.

00:06:43.135 --> 00:06:46.237
Jon: It's an astonishing
amount of leverage,

00:06:46.237 --> 00:06:48.737
but what this also points to is that,

00:06:48.737 --> 00:06:51.857
I was watching a ted talk that Bill Gates

00:06:51.857 --> 00:06:54.448
gave recently and part of the video was

00:06:54.448 --> 00:06:56.536
discussing education ... And you know from

00:06:56.536 --> 00:06:57.947
the software business, that there's this

00:06:57.947 --> 00:07:01.236
mime about there being
a really big difference

00:07:01.236 --> 00:07:04.277
between an average software engineer and

00:07:04.277 --> 00:07:06.857
a great software engineer; it's not just

00:07:06.857 --> 00:07:12.460
twice as good, it's [overdirect] magnitude

00:07:12.460 --> 00:07:14.136
difference, or at least this is the claim.

00:07:14.136 --> 00:07:16.224
He was making that same
argument in the realm

00:07:16.224 --> 00:07:18.691
of education and that the Gates Foundation

00:07:18.691 --> 00:07:21.274
had been looking into
this and had concluded

00:07:21.274 --> 00:07:22.186
that it's the same, right?

00:07:22.186 --> 00:07:25.636
That there are some teachers who are just

00:07:25.636 --> 00:07:28.635
way, way better than average and how

00:07:28.635 --> 00:07:31.135
can we leverage that?

00:07:31.135 --> 00:07:33.036
What you're doing is
a perfect illustration

00:07:33.036 --> 00:07:34.427
of how we could leverage that.

00:07:34.427 --> 00:07:36.536
I want to ask you about ...

00:07:36.536 --> 00:07:41.234
Clearly you're a great
teacher and you love to do it,

00:07:41.234 --> 00:07:44.444
but when did you realize that?

00:07:44.444 --> 00:07:47.932
What is it about you and how you think and

00:07:47.932 --> 00:07:52.537
how you present things
and how you communicate?

00:07:52.537 --> 00:07:54.838
Have you analyzed what it is that

00:07:54.838 --> 00:07:56.191
you think is effective?

00:07:56.191 --> 00:08:02.196
Sal: I've tried to. I
think about that myself.

00:08:02.196 --> 00:08:05.370
The idea of putting instruction on the web

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:06.837
and letting people use it isn't new,

00:08:06.837 --> 00:08:08.280
I wasn't the first person to think of it,

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:11.607
so I do introspect a lot as to why these

00:08:11.607 --> 00:08:13.945
videos have seemed to have struck a chord

00:08:13.945 --> 00:08:16.137
with people and gotten a lot of traction.

00:08:16.137 --> 00:08:17.734
I think it's a couple of things...

00:08:17.734 --> 00:08:20.415
You ask when did I realize it?

00:08:20.415 --> 00:08:24.316
I think this is true of a lot of people,

00:08:24.316 --> 00:08:25.230
it's probably true of yourself,

00:08:25.230 --> 00:08:26.143
or a lot of people who do well in the

00:08:26.143 --> 00:08:29.237
Math and Sciences, is
they kind of go beyond

00:08:29.237 --> 00:08:30.645
what's going on in the classroom and

00:08:30.645 --> 00:08:31.940
make connections on their own.

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:33.338
If anything, they get frustrated by

00:08:33.338 --> 00:08:34.566
what goes on in the classroom.

00:08:34.566 --> 00:08:38.739
They see otherwise intelligent
peers memorizing facts

00:08:38.739 --> 00:08:41.830
and not really caring
about the actual intuition,

00:08:41.830 --> 00:08:43.238
and because they didn't
care about the intuition

00:08:43.238 --> 00:08:46.238
in their junior year, when
that same idea pops up

00:08:46.238 --> 00:08:49.738
in the senior year, it's like
they've never seen it before.

00:08:49.738 --> 00:08:53.071
It would boggle my mind,
you're relabeling the same

00:08:53.071 --> 00:08:54.641
concept over and over.

00:08:54.641 --> 00:08:55.835
I've always had the frustration.

00:08:55.835 --> 00:08:59.580
I've always been someone that always liked

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:01.736
to ponder what I was
learning as opposed to,

00:09:01.736 --> 00:09:04.241
and sometimes it was
at my detriment because

00:09:04.241 --> 00:09:06.052
you only have so much time in your day

00:09:06.052 --> 00:09:07.636
and you can either do what the teacher

00:09:07.636 --> 00:09:09.236
tells you to do or you can ponder.

00:09:09.236 --> 00:09:10.835
The pondering might pay
off in the long term,

00:09:10.835 --> 00:09:13.138
but not doing what the
teacher tells you to do

00:09:13.138 --> 00:09:15.935
is what will hurt you in the short term.

00:09:15.935 --> 00:09:17.811
That was kind of my
frustration with my education

00:09:17.811 --> 00:09:20.033
throughout high school and college.

00:09:20.033 --> 00:09:21.836
I was kind of the guy
who'd skip class a lot

00:09:21.836 --> 00:09:24.303
and just try to read a
book, then read other books

00:09:24.303 --> 00:09:26.054
and talk to my friends about the concept

00:09:26.054 --> 00:09:28.138
as opposed to necessarily going to classes

00:09:28.138 --> 00:09:31.134
because I felt I was either lost in class

00:09:31.134 --> 00:09:33.641
or I was bored in class.

00:09:33.641 --> 00:09:35.561
On a good class, maybe
there'd be 10 minutes

00:09:35.561 --> 00:09:39.144
where it was catering
to me and so that was

00:09:39.144 --> 00:09:41.894
also a very frustrating experience.

00:09:41.894 --> 00:09:46.471
It really felt like there
must be a better way.

00:09:46.471 --> 00:09:49.835
When I started tutoring my cousin Nadia,

00:09:49.835 --> 00:09:53.473
I started tutoring her
as a friend, or a cousin

00:09:53.473 --> 00:09:55.557
as opposed to a teacher.

00:09:55.557 --> 00:09:58.731
I think that tone, if
I had to pick one thing

00:09:58.731 --> 00:10:01.735
that has kind of resonated with people,

00:10:01.735 --> 00:10:03.057
it's this tone that ...

00:10:03.057 --> 00:10:05.139
I got a note the other
day on the YouTube Channel

00:10:05.139 --> 00:10:07.476
where, "You teach more like
a friend than a teacher."

00:10:07.476 --> 00:10:09.224
Jon: Yeah, conversational tone.

00:10:09.224 --> 00:10:10.557
Sal: You interpret that in multiple ways,

00:10:10.557 --> 00:10:13.552
but I think that's the core issue ...

00:10:13.552 --> 00:10:15.837
That the tone doesn't turn people off.

00:10:15.837 --> 00:10:19.145
The next thing what I touched
on in my own experience

00:10:19.145 --> 00:10:21.356
is that I'm really big
on making connections.

00:10:21.356 --> 00:10:23.447
I get a lot of letters
and you can almost sense

00:10:23.447 --> 00:10:26.047
the anger from the students where they

00:10:26.047 --> 00:10:28.355
communicate that their teachers think

00:10:28.355 --> 00:10:30.274
they're making it easier
for the students by

00:10:30.274 --> 00:10:33.188
not giving the intuition,
by not giving the depth

00:10:33.188 --> 00:10:34.857
or making the connections because they

00:10:34.857 --> 00:10:36.345
kind of think that the
students just need to

00:10:36.345 --> 00:10:37.851
learn the mechanics.

00:10:37.851 --> 00:10:39.648
I get letter after letter saying because

00:10:39.648 --> 00:10:40.446
you get the intuition,

00:10:40.446 --> 00:10:42.855
because you give the common sense

00:10:42.855 --> 00:10:46.019
why this is just a mathematical way of

00:10:46.019 --> 00:10:47.741
expressing something that
makes a lot of sense,

00:10:47.741 --> 00:10:49.648
it actually becomes a lot more easy and

00:10:49.648 --> 00:10:51.609
a lot more intuitive.

00:10:51.609 --> 00:10:53.946
I think if you combine that with ...

00:10:53.946 --> 00:10:56.769
YouTube used to limit me to 10 minutes and

00:10:56.769 --> 00:10:58.778
I've gotten letters from
researchers telling me

00:10:58.778 --> 00:11:00.547
that it's been established that 9 minutes

00:11:00.547 --> 00:11:02.447
is about as long as
someone can really focus

00:11:02.447 --> 00:11:05.746
and pay attention without
taking a mental break.

00:11:05.746 --> 00:11:07.046
I give credit to YouTube for that.

00:11:07.046 --> 00:11:10.047
I now can record a little
bit longer than 10 minutes,

00:11:10.047 --> 00:11:11.451
but I think that's a big thing.

00:11:11.451 --> 00:11:12.946
The other thing, and
this was just a complete

00:11:12.946 --> 00:11:15.490
side effect of me trying to do it as

00:11:15.490 --> 00:11:17.104
cheaply as possible without fancy video

00:11:17.104 --> 00:11:19.446
equipment is, you don't see my face and

00:11:19.446 --> 00:11:21.194
I've been told by a lot of people that

00:11:21.194 --> 00:11:23.361
that keeps it from being a distraction.

00:11:23.361 --> 00:11:24.737
It actually makes it very easy for me to

00:11:24.737 --> 00:11:25.947
make the videos, I don't have to shave or

00:11:25.947 --> 00:11:29.447
wash my face (laughter)
before I make every video.

00:11:29.447 --> 00:11:32.688
I just have to make sure ...

00:11:32.688 --> 00:11:37.646
Jon: The process that you use is
apparently delightfully low-tech.

00:11:37.646 --> 00:11:41.359
It looks to me like you're using tools

00:11:41.359 --> 00:11:45.194
as simple as Windows Paint
and I don't know what,

00:11:45.194 --> 00:11:46.328
but it's nothing fancy, right?

00:11:46.328 --> 00:11:49.611
Sal: No, the first time where I decided to

00:11:49.611 --> 00:11:51.250
make the video, I said, "How can I make a

00:11:51.250 --> 00:11:53.109
decent video for my
cousins?" and I literally

00:11:53.109 --> 00:11:57.341
took Microsoft Paint,
made the background black,

00:11:57.341 --> 00:11:58.248
just because I thought it would look nice,

00:11:58.248 --> 00:12:01.547
like a chalkboard, and
I used some shareware

00:12:01.547 --> 00:12:03.773
screen capture software, it was like a

00:12:03.773 --> 00:12:05.146
"free for 20 days" and then you gotta pay

00:12:05.146 --> 00:12:09.548
$20 after that, I got myself a $20 headset

00:12:09.548 --> 00:12:14.153
and $60 Wacom Pen Tablet
and I started doing it.

00:12:14.153 --> 00:12:16.262
Actually, the production
quality was pretty good.

00:12:16.262 --> 00:12:19.430
The first, I would say,
4 or 500 videos were done

00:12:19.430 --> 00:12:20.767
exactly like that and you can see,

00:12:20.767 --> 00:12:22.144
if you see some of the earlier videos,

00:12:22.144 --> 00:12:25.144
they're now upgraded slightly,
but not really that much.

00:12:25.144 --> 00:12:28.350
One of the users just sent me a license

00:12:28.350 --> 00:12:29.849
to Camptasia; I think there's
other things I could use

00:12:29.849 --> 00:12:33.844
as well, that would do
screen capture fairly well.

00:12:33.844 --> 00:12:37.263
I now use a slightly better
art program that at least

00:12:37.263 --> 00:12:39.496
it's a little bit sensitive
to pressure on the

00:12:39.496 --> 00:12:41.883
pen tablet, but it's
still pretty low-tech.

00:12:41.883 --> 00:12:44.633
Jon: Yeah, exactly.

00:12:44.633 --> 00:12:48.133
It's interesting because
when I got started,

00:12:48.133 --> 00:12:51.710
I was actually, if you look on Wikipedia,

00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:53.967
I'm the person whose
name is associated with

00:12:53.967 --> 00:12:56.032
the word "Screencast"
because I got interested

00:12:56.032 --> 00:12:59.932
in that stuff some years ago and actually

00:12:59.932 --> 00:13:02.318
ran a little ... Because
I was making these

00:13:02.318 --> 00:13:06.132
software demos using
Camptasia and its predecessors

00:13:06.132 --> 00:13:10.144
and got real interested in that process.

00:13:10.144 --> 00:13:12.551
At a certain point, I got to where

00:13:12.551 --> 00:13:16.249
I was making pretty
highly-produced kinds of things

00:13:16.249 --> 00:13:18.661
that were tightly edited
and that was interesting

00:13:18.661 --> 00:13:22.328
to do that process, but at a later point,

00:13:22.328 --> 00:13:26.250
I started to rethink
that and at one moment

00:13:26.250 --> 00:13:28.447
I remember a friend of mine, his name is

00:13:28.447 --> 00:13:33.248
Chris [Gemignani] and
he's an Analytics and

00:13:33.248 --> 00:13:36.254
Visualization person,
and every once in a while

00:13:36.254 --> 00:13:39.548
he makes these screencasts to show people

00:13:39.548 --> 00:13:44.498
things that he can teach
them in say, Excel.

00:13:44.498 --> 00:13:47.663
He made one of these and it was full of

00:13:47.663 --> 00:13:50.658
stops and starts and you know,

00:13:50.658 --> 00:13:52.750
"Oh, I didn't mean to do it that way," and

00:13:52.750 --> 00:13:55.351
"Let's back up and try another path," and

00:13:55.351 --> 00:13:58.440
we talked about it afterwards and he said,

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:00.549
"You know, I felt like I
should edit that stuff,

00:14:00.549 --> 00:14:03.448
but then I realized in a way, if I did,

00:14:03.448 --> 00:14:05.658
I wouldn't be giving
people their true insight

00:14:05.658 --> 00:14:07.911
into the process of how I think about

00:14:07.911 --> 00:14:11.490
these things and how I do these things."

00:14:11.490 --> 00:14:14.546
In fact, the unedited style wound up being

00:14:14.546 --> 00:14:17.380
better and I think maybe
that's true for you, too.

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:21.046
Sal: Oh absolutely. That's probably one of

00:14:21.046 --> 00:14:22.883
the top three in terms of why ...

00:14:22.883 --> 00:14:24.880
It was really out of laziness initially.

00:14:24.880 --> 00:14:25.879
Jon: (laughs)

00:14:25.879 --> 00:14:27.148
Sal: It was for my cousins, I was like,

00:14:27.148 --> 00:14:29.338
"I don't care what they
think. I'm doing this

00:14:29.338 --> 00:14:32.146
out of my own ... ," so
I would put it out there.

00:14:32.146 --> 00:14:34.835
I wouldn't do the problem
before I made the video,

00:14:34.835 --> 00:14:38.648
so they saw me doing the
problems the first time.

00:14:38.648 --> 00:14:40.648
Every now and then, I
would go down one route

00:14:40.648 --> 00:14:42.848
and say, "Wait, that's
not right," and I would

00:14:42.848 --> 00:14:44.146
back up a little bit.

00:14:44.146 --> 00:14:47.248
That's something that
frankly, no one ever sees.

00:14:47.248 --> 00:14:50.148
Your lecturer in your
high school Trigonometry

00:14:50.148 --> 00:14:52.555
class, they have done the
problem ahead of time,

00:14:52.555 --> 00:14:54.553
or they have the solution
in front of them.

00:14:54.553 --> 00:14:55.646
You just see the finished product,

00:14:55.646 --> 00:14:57.245
you don't actually see
the thought process.

00:14:57.245 --> 00:14:58.746
I think to actually see
someone stumble around

00:14:58.746 --> 00:15:01.468
a little bit, who you
respect, who you realize

00:15:01.468 --> 00:15:03.377
knows what they're doing,
but still they stumble

00:15:03.377 --> 00:15:04.831
around and see kind of the art of solving

00:15:04.831 --> 00:15:06.894
a problem I think is
something you'll never see

00:15:06.894 --> 00:15:09.054
in a traditional lecture or textbook.

00:15:09.054 --> 00:15:11.510
Jon: That might also imply
that you do relatively

00:15:11.510 --> 00:15:14.142
less prep than another
person might imagine

00:15:14.142 --> 00:15:17.755
would be necessary because
thinking on your feet

00:15:17.755 --> 00:15:19.254
is part of the process.

00:15:19.254 --> 00:15:21.644
Sal: Now I kind of
embrace that idea now that

00:15:21.644 --> 00:15:23.841
there's more viewership,
I feel like I should

00:15:23.841 --> 00:15:25.528
prepare more and make it more polished,

00:15:25.528 --> 00:15:29.856
but I kind of fight that
instinct and I still

00:15:29.856 --> 00:15:31.510
want to keep them relatively raw.

00:15:31.510 --> 00:15:33.178
I want to make them easy to watch,

00:15:33.178 --> 00:15:38.175
but I get a lot of letters,
people appreciate these ...

00:15:38.175 --> 00:15:40.241
There's the college board SAT book and

00:15:40.241 --> 00:15:41.937
I did all 400 Math
problems and I literally

00:15:41.937 --> 00:15:43.545
did them in real time so ...

00:15:43.545 --> 00:15:45.260
Literally like sitting
on my shoulder while

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:47.346
I take an SAT exam which is a kind of,

00:15:47.346 --> 00:15:50.336
I don't think a lot of people will expose

00:15:50.336 --> 00:15:54.870
themselves in that way,
but I think it's an

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:55.522
incredibly valuable experience because you

00:15:55.522 --> 00:15:58.545
don't actually get to
see that in real life.

00:15:58.545 --> 00:16:00.845
Jon: In so many ways, we
never get the opportunity

00:16:00.845 --> 00:16:04.841
to look over the shoulder
of a practitioner,

00:16:04.841 --> 00:16:06.231
of any discipline.

00:16:06.231 --> 00:16:09.512
This has been one of my biggest hopes for

00:16:09.512 --> 00:16:12.141
the medium of internet
video, as a matter of fact,

00:16:12.141 --> 00:16:15.674
is that exactly that becomes possible.

00:16:15.674 --> 00:16:22.142
I've thought a lot about how in earlier

00:16:22.142 --> 00:16:25.510
incarnations of human society,
that was really the norm.

00:16:25.510 --> 00:16:30.677
When you were living
in tribal or a village

00:16:30.677 --> 00:16:34.542
kind of situation, the
work that people did

00:16:34.542 --> 00:16:36.443
was visible to you, right?

00:16:36.443 --> 00:16:38.534
You just had to look and
see what people were doing.

00:16:38.534 --> 00:16:40.543
It was just out there in the open and so

00:16:40.543 --> 00:16:45.340
part of education was just
seeing what people did.

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:47.755
In a funny kind of way,
I realized that when

00:16:47.755 --> 00:16:49.443
got to this mode where
we were all in cubicles

00:16:49.443 --> 00:16:54.343
with keyboards and screens,
but were communicating

00:16:54.343 --> 00:16:55.943
through email and communicating through

00:16:55.943 --> 00:16:59.430
these other sort of mediated channels,

00:16:59.430 --> 00:17:01.988
in a way, we actually lose the ability to

00:17:01.988 --> 00:17:03.835
watch other people, to
see how they work with

00:17:03.835 --> 00:17:05.942
their tools to see how
their minds work, right?

00:17:05.942 --> 00:17:10.404
So like with capturing that
is a really interesting

00:17:10.404 --> 00:17:13.154
possibility for the
medium of internet video,

00:17:13.154 --> 00:17:16.430
and you're a great illustration of that.

00:17:16.430 --> 00:17:18.743
Sal: I 100% agree and I think that extends

00:17:18.743 --> 00:17:20.432
even beyond what I'm doing.

00:17:20.432 --> 00:17:25.459
I won't name him because the story isn't

00:17:25.459 --> 00:17:27.544
flattering to his
company, but he's kind of

00:17:27.544 --> 00:17:29.454
used my example and he does analytics

00:17:29.454 --> 00:17:31.935
at a company and he was
running some reports.

00:17:31.935 --> 00:17:33.736
Instead of writing a white paper on what

00:17:33.736 --> 00:17:35.955
this report means or how do you run it,

00:17:35.955 --> 00:17:38.540
like you would traditionally
do in a corporation,

00:17:38.540 --> 00:17:39.835
he told the CEO of the company,

00:17:39.835 --> 00:17:41.704
"I have this buddy, he
does this thing on YouTube

00:17:41.704 --> 00:17:43.721
using Camptasia. How
about I do the same thing?

00:17:43.721 --> 00:17:45.380
Instead of running a white
paper on how to do it,

00:17:45.380 --> 00:17:47.235
how about I just capture
my screen while I do it

00:17:47.235 --> 00:17:48.433
and I'll talk out loud and ... ."

00:17:48.433 --> 00:17:50.636
I thought it was a brilliant idea.

00:17:50.636 --> 00:17:52.334
What better way than the guy who's kind of

00:17:52.334 --> 00:17:54.737
writing it to learn from
looking over his shoulder

00:17:54.737 --> 00:17:58.136
how he does it, but she
thought it was silly.

00:17:58.136 --> 00:18:00.540
Just because I think
it's not how the other

00:18:00.540 --> 00:18:02.463
corporations do it or it's not how the

00:18:02.463 --> 00:18:04.374
corporation she worked for did it.

00:18:04.374 --> 00:18:05.458
I think it's going to happen.

00:18:05.458 --> 00:18:08.335
I think a lot of these
short technical papers

00:18:08.335 --> 00:18:10.460
are going to become
obsolete because people

00:18:10.460 --> 00:18:11.873
can just look over someone's shoulder

00:18:11.873 --> 00:18:13.330
and see how they do it in real time.

00:18:13.330 --> 00:18:16.948
Jon: There's a video
that you may have seen by

00:18:16.948 --> 00:18:19.779
this guy, Hans Rosling.
He wrote the Gapminder

00:18:19.779 --> 00:18:23.192
software which is this
pretty incredible data

00:18:23.192 --> 00:18:24.864
visualization, he's given
a couple of Ted talks,

00:18:24.864 --> 00:18:29.236
and what you realize
when you see him giving

00:18:29.236 --> 00:18:33.236
one of these presentations,
is that it's only

00:18:33.236 --> 00:18:37.446
partly about the high quality
animated visualizations

00:18:37.446 --> 00:18:39.858
which the software can produce.

00:18:39.858 --> 00:18:43.727
It's also about how he performs

00:18:43.727 --> 00:18:48.356
the presentation around that, so it's the

00:18:48.356 --> 00:18:51.736
combination of him using the software

00:18:51.736 --> 00:18:53.734
along with his voice, along with his body

00:18:53.734 --> 00:18:56.126
in this case to illustrate.

00:18:56.126 --> 00:18:58.135
That is incredibly powerful.

00:18:58.550 --> 00:19:04.356
What I wanted to get to, though, was where

00:19:04.356 --> 00:19:08.533
are the limitations still
and how can we address

00:19:08.533 --> 00:19:10.934
them ... so one thing a person doesn't

00:19:10.934 --> 00:19:13.318
get to do is interact with you.

00:19:13.318 --> 00:19:17.443
It's one way in the
course of these videos,

00:19:17.443 --> 00:19:24.359
so it's not sort of a complete replacement

00:19:24.359 --> 00:19:27.633
for much or some of
what happens in school,

00:19:27.633 --> 00:19:30.632
it's however, a useful
compliment and I have

00:19:30.632 --> 00:19:35.939
read some indications
that people are getting to

00:19:35.939 --> 00:19:38.447
combine your stuff with classrooms in

00:19:38.447 --> 00:19:40.358
interactive settings.

00:19:40.358 --> 00:19:42.532
So what do you think about that?

00:19:42.532 --> 00:19:46.032
Sal: When I started this,
that was kind of my sense;

00:19:46.032 --> 00:19:47.944
it doesn't have the interactivity of

00:19:47.944 --> 00:19:53.228
a live one-on-one session,
but I've come to the

00:19:53.228 --> 00:19:55.443
conclusion, I don't
want to be too grandiose

00:19:55.443 --> 00:19:59.693
about its potential,
but I do think that it's

00:19:59.693 --> 00:20:03.034
hands-down better than
the professor sitting

00:20:03.034 --> 00:20:05.280
in front of a classroom
of 300 students and

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:08.949
just lecturing a prepared
scripted lecture to them.

00:20:08.949 --> 00:20:12.634
One, that's kind of
artificial, it's a 90 minute

00:20:12.634 --> 00:20:15.233
long thing, it's probably
not catering to all

00:20:15.233 --> 00:20:16.777
of the students, some of
the students are lost,

00:20:16.777 --> 00:20:19.934
some are bored, they might be sleepy,

00:20:19.934 --> 00:20:20.939
it's just not the time ...

00:20:20.939 --> 00:20:22.864
Jon: There's no question about that.

00:20:22.864 --> 00:20:24.532
Sal: So here you're getting
it when you want it,

00:20:24.532 --> 00:20:26.784
you're getting it in granular chunks,

00:20:26.784 --> 00:20:30.134
and you can pause, repeat
if I say "orthogonal"

00:20:30.134 --> 00:20:31.641
and you don't know what that means,

00:20:31.641 --> 00:20:34.043
you can pause and look it up on Wikipedia,

00:20:34.043 --> 00:20:36.336
you can go look at the
other video that I've done

00:20:36.336 --> 00:20:39.045
on orthogonality and fill in
the blanks just to review.

00:20:39.045 --> 00:20:41.882
I think on a lot of levels,
like my cousin said,

00:20:41.882 --> 00:20:46.515
I'm better in a lot of
lectures ... Would be better on

00:20:46.515 --> 00:20:48.432
YouTube than live.

00:20:48.432 --> 00:20:51.631
Then there's also the
opportunity to really

00:20:51.631 --> 00:20:54.500
tweak it where YouTube
gives me data on where

00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:55.874
attention span drops off from my videos,

00:20:55.874 --> 00:20:57.886
so if something unusual
happens in one of my

00:20:57.886 --> 00:20:59.964
videos, I can go back to that point,

00:20:59.964 --> 00:21:02.135
see what happened, maybe
record another video

00:21:02.135 --> 00:21:04.480
if it's because I threw
out a weird concept

00:21:04.480 --> 00:21:05.735
or I skipped a step or whatever.

00:21:05.735 --> 00:21:06.542
Jon: Exactly.

00:21:06.542 --> 00:21:09.728
Sal: So there's also this
potential of really tweeking.

00:21:09.728 --> 00:21:11.827
That's why I want to do this software,

00:21:11.827 --> 00:21:13.310
and I've been working on the software,

00:21:13.310 --> 00:21:14.709
because I want to see
how people interact with

00:21:14.709 --> 00:21:17.334
exercises before and after
the video interaction.

00:21:17.334 --> 00:21:19.715
Attention span is one thing,
but I also want to see

00:21:19.715 --> 00:21:21.433
whether they learned.

00:21:21.433 --> 00:21:24.242
You can imagine a world
where you make a video

00:21:24.242 --> 00:21:25.738
or I make a video or we
make multiple versions

00:21:25.738 --> 00:21:27.734
of the same video and
we just see which ones

00:21:27.734 --> 00:21:29.160
work best for different people.

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:30.816
Jon: Absolutely.

00:21:30.816 --> 00:21:32.132
Sal: There's things that have never been

00:21:32.132 --> 00:21:33.831
imagined with traditional.

00:21:33.831 --> 00:21:36.310
The limitation I think,
is just that notion that

00:21:36.310 --> 00:21:39.310
there's this individual who
cares directly about you.

00:21:39.310 --> 00:21:40.533
When I worked first
worked with my cousins,

00:21:40.533 --> 00:21:43.076
I think it's that idea
of my 12-year-old cousin

00:21:43.076 --> 00:21:47.239
feeling like her, at the
time I was 26-year-old,

00:21:47.239 --> 00:21:50.718
cousin who took time out
of his day to mentor her.

00:21:50.718 --> 00:21:52.658
I think that's incredibly,
incredibly valuable.

00:21:52.658 --> 00:21:55.654
Frankly, that's not going on in the school

00:21:55.654 --> 00:21:56.510
system right now, right?

00:21:56.510 --> 00:21:58.432
Right now you're lucky if
you have a conversation

00:21:58.432 --> 00:22:01.511
with your teacher in
a class of 30 and it's

00:22:01.511 --> 00:22:03.738
usually the problem kids who are having

00:22:03.738 --> 00:22:05.131
the most time with the
teacher and it's not

00:22:05.131 --> 00:22:06.744
a positive interaction.

00:22:06.744 --> 00:22:09.655
Jon: I'll tell you a
funny story about some

00:22:09.655 --> 00:22:13.840
other educational videos that I've seen.

00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:17.231
I catch a lot of this
stuff in podcast form

00:22:17.231 --> 00:22:21.432
and at one point I was
kind of auditing a course

00:22:21.432 --> 00:22:26.233
on Evolutionary Biology out
of, I think it was Berkley,

00:22:26.233 --> 00:22:29.431
so I remembered actually
something I had seen

00:22:29.431 --> 00:22:33.248
in that course a couple
of years before and

00:22:33.248 --> 00:22:35.670
I wanted to use that
insight in something I was

00:22:35.670 --> 00:22:37.434
writing on my blog.

00:22:37.434 --> 00:22:41.521
I went back to try to find it and

00:22:41.521 --> 00:22:42.673
when I went back to look at it,

00:22:42.673 --> 00:22:45.433
I wound up doing the video instead of

00:22:45.433 --> 00:22:48.231
the audio like I usually
do, and my daughter,

00:22:48.231 --> 00:22:49.934
who was just getting
ready to enter college,

00:22:49.934 --> 00:22:52.667
was looking over my shoulder while I was

00:22:52.667 --> 00:22:54.750
playing this video and she said,

00:22:54.750 --> 00:22:57.433
"So, do the students just sit there?"

00:22:57.433 --> 00:22:59.755
(laughter)

00:22:59.755 --> 00:23:02.751
Jon: I was like, "Yeah." In a
large lecture, they do, right?

00:23:02.751 --> 00:23:04.733
But then the other weird
thing about that was

00:23:04.733 --> 00:23:08.732
that when I finally found
that installment of the

00:23:08.732 --> 00:23:12.673
course, he wasn't as good
... What they had done

00:23:12.673 --> 00:23:15.734
is they had replaced
this semester's version

00:23:15.734 --> 00:23:20.233
with the version from two
years ago that I had seen.

00:23:20.233 --> 00:23:23.131
He'd been better two years ago.

00:23:23.131 --> 00:23:26.435
It was like he had the
more effective version

00:23:26.435 --> 00:23:29.132
so why not just can
that and reuse that and

00:23:29.132 --> 00:23:32.588
use the class time for supplementary

00:23:32.588 --> 00:23:35.032
kinds of things, or
interactive kinds of things.

00:23:35.032 --> 00:23:36.724
Sal: I've got several other teachers,

