00:25:19.431 --> 00:25:21.332
what works for different people.

00:25:21.332 --> 00:25:24.332
Jon: Right. So say a little bit more about

00:25:24.332 --> 00:25:27.139
the software you're
working on, what it will do

00:25:27.139 --> 00:25:29.200
and where it's going.

00:25:29.200 --> 00:25:30.474
Sal: It already exists on
the side, I've actually

00:25:30.474 --> 00:25:34.624
just had to [port it and app end] because

00:25:34.624 --> 00:25:36.834
too many people were using it which is not

00:25:36.834 --> 00:25:39.386
a bad problem, but when
you're the support staff

00:25:39.386 --> 00:25:42.140
and engineering staff ...

00:25:42.140 --> 00:25:45.806
The idea's very simple;
it starts at 1 + 1 = 2,

00:25:45.806 --> 00:25:48.534
it just generates random problems and

00:25:48.534 --> 00:25:51.135
each module is like a concept,

00:25:51.135 --> 00:25:54.304
like basic addition; 1
+ 1 = 2, 2 + 3 = 5 ...

00:25:54.304 --> 00:25:55.932
You got to get 10 in a row.

00:25:55.932 --> 00:25:58.146
Once you have 10 in a row on that,

00:25:58.146 --> 00:26:00.437
and that's something that doesn't

00:26:00.437 --> 00:26:01.332
happen in the school system,

00:26:01.332 --> 00:26:02.641
no one expects you to get 10 in a row.

00:26:02.641 --> 00:26:05.055
They expect you to get
70% and then you move on.

00:26:05.055 --> 00:26:07.890
You get 10 in a row and then it's kind of,

00:26:07.890 --> 00:26:09.390
if you can imagine a no-directed graph,

00:26:09.390 --> 00:26:11.234
I have something called
a "Knowledge Map" and

00:26:11.234 --> 00:26:13.148
your basic addition,
once you get 10 in a row,

00:26:13.148 --> 00:26:14.970
you've then fulfilled
the prerequisites for

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:17.723
Level 2 Addition and Basic Subtraction.

00:26:17.723 --> 00:26:19.932
Those fulfill the
prerequisites and you have this

00:26:19.932 --> 00:26:23.469
no-directed graph, right
now it goes up through

00:26:23.469 --> 00:26:26.558
pretty much all of Algebra
2 and Trigonometry.

00:26:26.558 --> 00:26:29.433
The videos on YouTube go well beyond that.

00:26:29.433 --> 00:26:31.967
They go into college-level
Math, Physics and

00:26:31.967 --> 00:26:35.232
Chemistry, but the software,
the idea is to have

00:26:35.232 --> 00:26:37.140
it at least cover everything
you would have to know

00:26:37.140 --> 00:26:41.233
for the SAT, the ACT or take the GED.

00:26:41.233 --> 00:26:45.332
The problems are randomly generated,

00:26:45.332 --> 00:26:48.833
so if it takes you 500
problems to understand

00:26:48.833 --> 00:26:50.473
negative exponents, you're going to get

00:26:50.473 --> 00:26:52.055
500 problems and in the process,

00:26:52.055 --> 00:26:53.832
it's tracking everything
you do and it knows when ...

00:26:53.832 --> 00:26:56.226
The videos are coupled into it so if you

00:26:56.226 --> 00:26:58.332
get a problem, if you know how to do it,

00:26:58.332 --> 00:26:59.637
you can type in the answer.

00:26:59.637 --> 00:27:00.468
If you don't know how to do it,

00:27:00.468 --> 00:27:01.532
you can click "Hint", it'll give you the

00:27:01.532 --> 00:27:03.632
steps for that exact problem.

00:27:03.632 --> 00:27:04.731
If you still don't know how to do it,

00:27:04.731 --> 00:27:06.334
you can click "Video" and the video from

00:27:06.334 --> 00:27:07.432
YouTube will pipe in.

00:27:07.432 --> 00:27:10.537
What I kind of envision
doing is closing the

00:27:10.537 --> 00:27:13.834
loop between instruction,
practice and assessment

00:27:13.834 --> 00:27:15.554
and making them all happen simultaneously

00:27:15.554 --> 00:27:17.435
as opposed to the traditional model where

00:27:17.435 --> 00:27:19.642
I lecture to you, I
give you homework which

00:27:19.642 --> 00:27:21.472
you do in a complete
vacuum without any feedback

00:27:21.472 --> 00:27:22.971
because the textbooks aren't giving you

00:27:22.971 --> 00:27:24.335
any feedback and you may or may not know

00:27:24.335 --> 00:27:26.976
how to do it, and then
we kind of keep going

00:27:26.976 --> 00:27:28.933
in that cycle for a week or two and then

00:27:28.933 --> 00:27:31.053
I give you an exam, you get a C,

00:27:31.053 --> 00:27:32.736
so you clearly have some deficiencies,

00:27:32.736 --> 00:27:34.932
but too bad, we have to
move onto the next concept.

00:27:34.932 --> 00:27:39.137
The model here is just close the loop and

00:27:39.137 --> 00:27:41.558
don't let anyone have any deficiencies

00:27:41.558 --> 00:27:43.514
before they move on.

00:27:43.514 --> 00:27:46.138
Jon: Is it also the case
that you're starting

00:27:46.138 --> 00:27:49.233
to get telemetry that's
telling you something

00:27:49.233 --> 00:27:50.960
about the videos, how
they're being used and

00:27:50.960 --> 00:27:54.136
what the before and after comparison is?

00:27:54.136 --> 00:27:56.707
Sal: The software
integration, I've done it

00:27:56.707 --> 00:27:59.237
pretty heavily with a
couple of summer camps

00:27:59.237 --> 00:28:03.380
out here in the Bay Area
and I haven't gotten

00:28:03.380 --> 00:28:05.549
to the point yet where
I'm testing two videos

00:28:05.549 --> 00:28:06.437
on the same concept.

00:28:06.437 --> 00:28:08.522
I don't have a lot of
multiple videos for the

00:28:08.522 --> 00:28:10.638
same concept yet, so I'm
tweaking on that level,

00:28:10.638 --> 00:28:15.215
but we have seen, we
did it with a group of

00:28:15.215 --> 00:28:17.627
rising 8th graders; these were low and

00:28:17.627 --> 00:28:19.962
middle income, mainly minority students,

00:28:19.962 --> 00:28:21.548
and this was a summer program to get them

00:28:21.548 --> 00:28:25.528
prepared for Algebra and pre-Algebra.

00:28:25.528 --> 00:28:26.878
We saw it. When we started the students at

00:28:26.878 --> 00:28:30.236
1 + 1 = 2, there were just
some subset of students

00:28:30.236 --> 00:28:33.237
who had just very, very
basic deficiencies;

00:28:33.237 --> 00:28:37.545
subtracting decimals or
multiplying negative numbers.

00:28:37.545 --> 00:28:40.138
You could see it in the
data, they spent a little

00:28:40.138 --> 00:28:42.051
more time on those concepts and everyone

00:28:42.051 --> 00:28:43.838
else in the class, everyone
else thought it was

00:28:43.838 --> 00:28:46.337
just a review, but these
students, it was a gap.

00:28:46.337 --> 00:28:47.637
Once they got through that gap,

00:28:47.637 --> 00:28:49.050
they raced forward and
they were just as good

00:28:49.050 --> 00:28:50.340
as anybody else.

00:28:50.340 --> 00:28:52.546
I think that speaks to
why there's a lot of ...

00:28:52.546 --> 00:28:54.043
If you go into an Algebra
class, and there's

00:28:54.043 --> 00:28:56.381
a lot of great teachers
with high potential

00:28:56.381 --> 00:28:58.737
students talking past each other because

00:28:58.737 --> 00:29:02.031
the teacher can't address
the arithmetic issue

00:29:02.031 --> 00:29:04.136
and the student may
not even know they have

00:29:04.136 --> 00:29:06.338
that deficiency, or if they
do, they're embarrassed

00:29:06.338 --> 00:29:08.382
to bring it up, so when
you allow people to

00:29:08.382 --> 00:29:11.237
do this at their own pace,
you do see it in the data

00:29:11.237 --> 00:29:14.437
that it's actually hard to predict who's

00:29:14.437 --> 00:29:16.543
going to end up at
different points because

00:29:16.543 --> 00:29:19.050
if you give someone the
time to fill in their gaps,

00:29:19.050 --> 00:29:20.629
you might have thought
that they were a slow

00:29:20.629 --> 00:29:22.111
student before, but
once that gap is filled,

00:29:22.111 --> 00:29:24.433
they actually progress quite fast.

00:29:24.433 --> 00:29:27.725
Jon: It seems on the one
hand, unimaginable that

00:29:27.725 --> 00:29:32.034
we could be here in the
21st century and not

00:29:32.034 --> 00:29:36.034
have widely-available
tools online already for

00:29:36.034 --> 00:29:37.818
people to do those kinds of things,

00:29:37.818 --> 00:29:39.534
to do those kinds of remediations,

00:29:39.534 --> 00:29:41.833
but on the other hand, I
guess it seemed kind of

00:29:41.833 --> 00:29:44.431
unimaginable that millions
of people would be

00:29:44.431 --> 00:29:45.933
driving past this freeway intersection ...

00:29:45.933 --> 00:29:47.833
(laughter)

00:29:47.833 --> 00:29:50.433
Nobody bothered to tell
them where North 5 was.

00:29:50.433 --> 00:29:57.218
Sal: The freeway intersection,
that one's actually,

00:29:57.218 --> 00:30:01.248
in the education context,
there's some obvious

00:30:01.248 --> 00:30:04.333
forces as to why that doesn't exist today.

00:30:04.333 --> 00:30:06.434
I think everyone who's trying to innovate

00:30:06.434 --> 00:30:08.634
in education is trying to do it within the

00:30:08.634 --> 00:30:10.661
current context so
they're trying to go into

00:30:10.661 --> 00:30:13.432
school systems and try
to incrementally change

00:30:13.432 --> 00:30:15.388
what teachers are doing
one way or the other.

00:30:15.388 --> 00:30:19.333
It's very hard to move
the beast, so to speak.

00:30:19.333 --> 00:30:21.432
Then you have all these people on the

00:30:21.432 --> 00:30:23.118
for-profit realm and I don't know,

00:30:23.118 --> 00:30:24.325
they're just trying to sell something for

00:30:24.325 --> 00:30:26.255
$19.95 a month and I
don't think they're ...

00:30:26.255 --> 00:30:27.830
They're thinking too deeply about how

00:30:27.830 --> 00:30:30.639
to do it right, regardless
of economic consequences.

00:30:30.639 --> 00:30:32.757
Jon: You're right. I think
it almost has to come

00:30:32.757 --> 00:30:35.665
from the outside and ...
I don't know if you know

00:30:35.665 --> 00:30:37.749
Graham Glass, he's a
friend of mine and he's

00:30:37.749 --> 00:30:41.633
working on service called EDU 2.0 ...

00:30:41.633 --> 00:30:42.846
Sal: EDU 2.0?

00:30:42.846 --> 00:30:46.671
Jon: You might be curious about that.

00:30:46.671 --> 00:30:49.000
He's coming at it partly from a courseware

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:53.418
perspective, but also very
much from a project-based

00:30:53.418 --> 00:30:58.252
learning perspective
where the notion is ...

00:30:58.252 --> 00:30:59.844
It's kind of like this, right?

00:30:59.844 --> 00:31:02.740
I could have in my
school, I could have a kid

00:31:02.740 --> 00:31:04.839
who's interested in, I don't know,

00:31:04.839 --> 00:31:11.085
making and flying rockets, and there might

00:31:11.085 --> 00:31:13.252
or might not be somebody in the school who

00:31:13.252 --> 00:31:15.526
could mentor the kid.

00:31:15.526 --> 00:31:17.325
If there is, then you
have one of those lucky

00:31:17.325 --> 00:31:19.170
circumstances where the kid has a great

00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:23.841
experience and if not,
that capability goes

00:31:23.841 --> 00:31:27.753
untapped in the kid, but on the internet,

00:31:27.753 --> 00:31:29.664
we have the possibility to bring people

00:31:29.664 --> 00:31:31.761
together across time and space, right?

00:31:31.761 --> 00:31:34.841
So you have the possibility of bringing a

00:31:34.841 --> 00:31:39.250
mentor in from someplace
else and assembling

00:31:39.250 --> 00:31:43.826
mentors and students
in that way and letting

00:31:43.826 --> 00:31:46.225
them actually then pursue the stuff that

00:31:46.225 --> 00:31:48.941
excites them and do things, that's a nice

00:31:48.941 --> 00:31:52.337
complimentary model;
but again, he's coming

00:31:52.337 --> 00:31:56.762
completely from the
outside and I think that's

00:31:56.762 --> 00:31:59.441
probably where all the interesting action

00:31:59.441 --> 00:32:01.748
is going to be, it's going to have to be.

00:32:01.748 --> 00:32:05.254
Sal: I agree. I think
that's where it's all going.

00:32:05.254 --> 00:32:07.673
You have similar to Kahn
Academy has video content,

00:32:07.673 --> 00:32:08.940
it's going to have
software, it's going to do

00:32:08.940 --> 00:32:11.433
analytics on what's working
for different students

00:32:11.433 --> 00:32:12.581
and where the different
students are, but then

00:32:12.581 --> 00:32:15.173
you overlay that with
kind of a peer-to-peer

00:32:15.173 --> 00:32:17.940
interaction like you just described where

00:32:17.940 --> 00:32:20.584
the software knows that for Sal,

00:32:20.584 --> 00:32:22.435
the videos haven't been enough and even

00:32:22.435 --> 00:32:25.240
the software, he's struggling with it,

00:32:25.240 --> 00:32:30.587
I know his schedule and
I know a schedule of

00:32:30.587 --> 00:32:35.140
a young woman in Mexico City who's proven

00:32:35.140 --> 00:32:38.626
through the site that she
knows what she's doing

00:32:38.626 --> 00:32:39.921
and she's a high-regarded tutor,

00:32:39.921 --> 00:32:41.585
maybe she might be the same age as Sal or

00:32:41.585 --> 00:32:44.340
a little older or a practicing engineer or

00:32:44.340 --> 00:32:46.341
who knows what and you pair them up.

00:32:46.341 --> 00:32:49.257
You can even record the
interaction and then

00:32:49.257 --> 00:32:51.339
you capture the data,
the before and after,

00:32:51.339 --> 00:32:53.336
of Sal's performance and his ratings.

00:32:53.336 --> 00:32:55.757
Then all of a sudden, you have a very rich

00:32:55.757 --> 00:32:58.440
kind of peer-to-peer across time and space

00:32:58.440 --> 00:33:00.751
interactions amongst people all over.

00:33:00.751 --> 00:33:03.339
Obviously that has other
implications beyond

00:33:03.339 --> 00:33:05.430
just teaching people Math.

00:33:05.430 --> 00:33:07.639
It can do a lot in
terms of just awareness.

