curve is more than ...
You know, you're teaching

00:35:18.338 --> 00:35:20.237
30 or 25 kids so it's a
different concept than ...

00:35:20.237 --> 00:35:22.536
But I think they should be able to explain

00:35:22.536 --> 00:35:25.138
in a patient and empathetic way.

00:35:25.138 --> 00:35:26.368
What you know on YouTube,

00:35:26.368 --> 00:35:28.238
I think that's something,

00:35:28.238 --> 00:35:30.333
once you have a little bit of maturity,

00:35:30.333 --> 00:35:31.543
you'll probably be able to do as good as

00:35:31.543 --> 00:35:32.634
you'll ever be able to do it.

00:35:32.634 --> 00:35:38.039
Jon: Have you gotten
into areas where you are

00:35:38.039 --> 00:35:39.872
teaching yourself things that you hadn't

00:35:39.872 --> 00:35:42.208
previously known or known well?

00:35:42.208 --> 00:35:45.818
Sal: Oh yeah, tons of
... Frankly, that's the

00:35:45.818 --> 00:35:48.553
real fun for me is that I
get to revisit some things

00:35:48.553 --> 00:35:52.643
that I just did superficially
when I was in school

00:35:52.643 --> 00:35:55.539
and now I get to really
dive deep on my own

00:35:55.539 --> 00:35:57.453
timeframe without any pressure and really

00:35:57.453 --> 00:35:59.788
get to understand what those concepts are.

00:35:59.788 --> 00:36:01.137
The one example I was given was entropy.

00:36:01.137 --> 00:36:03.338
I wasn't a Chemistry jock in high school.

00:36:03.338 --> 00:36:05.436
I just did what I needed
to do to well in the class,

00:36:05.436 --> 00:36:07.637
but I didn't know it
intuitively the way I might have

00:36:07.637 --> 00:36:09.874
known Math or Computer Science,

00:36:09.874 --> 00:36:12.225
so that's been a great experience for me.

00:36:12.225 --> 00:36:14.822
I started in September
and I for two months,

00:36:14.822 --> 00:36:17.133
I really just became a Chemistry geek.

00:36:17.133 --> 00:36:18.737
I would call up my friends
who were professors

00:36:18.737 --> 00:36:20.437
at Stanford and MIT and say,

00:36:20.437 --> 00:36:23.375
"Hey, let's talk about entropy." (laughs)

00:36:23.375 --> 00:36:26.646
It's amazing, I think one
point of [unintelligible]

00:36:26.646 --> 00:36:29.325
I got from them is they envied me because

00:36:29.325 --> 00:36:31.840
when they were doing their PhDs,

00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:34.528
they couldn't go to their advisor and say,

00:36:34.528 --> 00:36:35.740
"Let's talk about entropy," because that's

00:36:35.740 --> 00:36:38.436
something that you were
supposed to have known

00:36:38.436 --> 00:36:40.840
when you took AP Chemistry or

00:36:40.840 --> 00:36:43.341
freshman level Chemistry,
but the reality is

00:36:43.341 --> 00:36:45.927
very few people do have
an intuition of say,

00:36:45.927 --> 00:36:50.539
entropy, including some professors today.

00:36:50.539 --> 00:36:53.820
Actually entropy examples,
once I was able to

00:36:53.820 --> 00:36:56.318
get the idea distilled in my mind,

00:36:56.318 --> 00:36:58.159
I realized that most
explanations out there

00:36:58.159 --> 00:37:01.238
were on some level, wrong.

00:37:01.238 --> 00:37:03.706
Jon: In what way?

00:37:03.706 --> 00:37:05.740
Sal: The way you learn
it in Chemistry class,

00:37:05.740 --> 00:37:08.539
the teacher says, "Entropy is disorder,"

00:37:08.539 --> 00:37:11.644
which isn't incorrect, but they say,

00:37:11.644 --> 00:37:13.787
"A clean room has low entropy and

00:37:13.787 --> 00:37:16.139
a dirty room has high entropy."

00:37:16.139 --> 00:37:18.142
So you go to the exam, they say,

00:37:18.142 --> 00:37:19.344
"This room is dirty, this one is clean.

00:37:19.344 --> 00:37:20.242
Which one has higher
entropy?" and you just

00:37:20.242 --> 00:37:22.238
kind of write it down.

00:37:22.238 --> 00:37:27.740
That's wrong. It's
missing the whole point of

00:37:27.740 --> 00:37:29.459
what entropy is. It took me a while to

00:37:29.459 --> 00:37:33.541
distill this idea that in Chemistry or

00:37:33.541 --> 00:37:36.045
Thermodynamics you have

00:37:36.045 --> 00:37:38.436
macrostates and microstates.

00:37:38.436 --> 00:37:40.378
Microstates are: you're
looking at a particular

00:37:40.378 --> 00:37:42.378
atom and you're looking
at its kinetic energy,

00:37:42.378 --> 00:37:43.342
you're looking at its momentum,

00:37:43.342 --> 00:37:45.433
you're looking at the
vector of its velocity,

00:37:45.433 --> 00:37:47.929
and if you looked at
the microstate of every

00:37:47.929 --> 00:37:49.532
little atom in a container,

00:37:49.532 --> 00:37:50.948
you could run a computer simulation and

00:37:50.948 --> 00:37:52.572
maybe might figure out what might happen

00:37:52.572 --> 00:37:55.813
the very next moment ...
Those are microstates.

00:37:55.813 --> 00:37:58.066
Macrostates are: you look
at the whole container

00:37:58.066 --> 00:38:01.748
and you describe all of the particles,

00:38:01.748 --> 00:38:03.980
almost you can think of
statistics for all the

00:38:03.980 --> 00:38:06.405
particles, so temperature is a macrostate;

00:38:06.405 --> 00:38:08.449
it's the average kinetic energy for all of

00:38:08.449 --> 00:38:11.350
the particles; so entropy similarly,

00:38:11.350 --> 00:38:14.853
is a macrostate, but it's
almost a metamacrostate.

00:38:14.853 --> 00:38:19.481
It's this idea of not what
state are the particles in,

00:38:19.481 --> 00:38:23.071
it's how many potential
states can the particles have.

00:38:23.071 --> 00:38:26.152
In the messy clean room analogy,

00:38:26.152 --> 00:38:27.566
the reason why I say
that's wrong is because

00:38:27.566 --> 00:38:29.749
each of those are particular states.

00:38:29.749 --> 00:38:32.845
It doesn't say, "A messy
room," it depends on

00:38:32.845 --> 00:38:34.530
what level you're
thinking about as states,

00:38:34.530 --> 00:38:36.946
but it has the same number, because of its

00:38:36.946 --> 00:38:39.429
temperature, its atoms
have the same number

00:38:39.429 --> 00:38:43.237
of potential states as the clean room.

00:38:43.237 --> 00:38:46.360
I guess I'll give you a
really hot, clean room

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:48.450
with things flying around in the air,

00:38:48.450 --> 00:38:51.946
is going to be higher entropy than

00:38:51.946 --> 00:38:53.734
a cold, dirty room with different things

00:38:53.734 --> 00:38:54.948
(laughs) are flying around in the air.

00:38:54.948 --> 00:38:56.444
Jon: (laughs)

00:38:56.444 --> 00:38:58.777
Sal: It's the number of
states that something

00:38:58.777 --> 00:39:00.700
can have and you can
even translate that into

00:39:00.700 --> 00:39:03.046
computer science. It's
the amount of information

00:39:03.046 --> 00:39:07.039
you need to describe
the state of a system.

00:39:07.039 --> 00:39:08.745
So if something that can have more states,

00:39:08.745 --> 00:39:11.365
you need to have more bits to describe its

00:39:11.365 --> 00:39:14.691
particular state ... And
that's completely lost,

00:39:14.691 --> 00:39:17.134
at least it was in the
Chemistry classes I took.

00:39:17.134 --> 00:39:20.423
Jon: That's good. I bet
one of the other areas

00:39:20.423 --> 00:39:23.236
that's going to be very
fruitful for you in

00:39:23.236 --> 00:39:27.476
coming years is Energy Literacy?

00:39:27.476 --> 00:39:29.980
Sal: These are questions ...

00:39:29.980 --> 00:39:32.836
A lot of people request
a lot of clean tech

00:39:32.836 --> 00:39:34.644
lectures, a lot of
people want me to settle

00:39:34.644 --> 00:39:37.555
the global warming debate,
the health care debate,

00:39:37.555 --> 00:39:40.434
these are things I look
forward to eventually.

00:39:40.434 --> 00:39:41.436
I don't know if I'm
going to be able to catch

00:39:41.436 --> 00:39:45.235
up with the kind of new cycle, but I think

00:39:45.235 --> 00:39:46.940
there is that opportunity
where I can dig deep

00:39:46.940 --> 00:39:50.394
into things and as
objectively as possible.

00:39:50.394 --> 00:39:51.735
I think people trust
me because they learned

00:39:51.735 --> 00:39:55.061
Calculus from me, that
I don't have a political

00:39:55.061 --> 00:39:57.973
kind of ax to grind and I can give them a

00:39:57.973 --> 00:40:01.640
fairly objective, hopefully
objective take on things.

00:40:01.640 --> 00:40:03.435
Jon: When I say energy literacy,

00:40:03.435 --> 00:40:05.234
I'm talking about, to give you an example,

00:40:05.234 --> 00:40:06.834
I was looking at some of
your stuff the other day

00:40:06.834 --> 00:40:09.020
and I've also been,
recently I've been hanging

00:40:09.020 --> 00:40:12.650
around on Wolfram Alpha a lot because it's

00:40:12.650 --> 00:40:18.234
a really helpful way of making conversions

00:40:18.234 --> 00:40:22.341
between units and
different forms of energy

00:40:22.341 --> 00:40:24.920
and matter and so on, and understanding

00:40:24.920 --> 00:40:29.840
like I don't know, I
put in my electric bill

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:31.742
was such-and-such kilowatt hours,

00:40:31.742 --> 00:40:33.657
it was like 1,200 kilowatt
hours, right, like

00:40:33.657 --> 00:40:35.718
"What is that? What
does that really mean?"

00:40:35.718 --> 00:40:38.018
It'll give it to you in terms of gasoline.

00:40:38.018 --> 00:40:38.802
Sal: That's cool.

00:40:38.802 --> 00:40:42.846
Jon: As a society, we are broadly speaking

00:40:42.846 --> 00:40:45.938
feeling like we need to
have a better handle on,

00:40:45.938 --> 00:40:49.350
"What does this stuff
really mean?" in terms that

00:40:49.350 --> 00:40:51.367
we can freely interconvert, and

00:40:51.367 --> 00:40:53.138
we're not so good at that.

00:40:53.138 --> 00:40:55.268
I went from one of your examples back to

00:40:55.268 --> 00:40:58.026
Wolfram Alpha and was thinking,

00:40:58.026 --> 00:41:01.677
I guess it was just the elevator that

00:41:01.677 --> 00:41:05.539
weighs so much and is
100 meters off the ground

00:41:05.539 --> 00:41:08.410
and it's got this much
potential energy and

00:41:08.410 --> 00:41:10.640
this much kinetic energy
when it hits the floor,

00:41:10.640 --> 00:41:13.837
and I looked at that relative
to gallons of gasoline

00:41:13.837 --> 00:41:16.138
and kilowatt hours of my electric bill and

00:41:16.138 --> 00:41:18.683
it was like wow, I
wouldn't have thought this,

00:41:18.683 --> 00:41:23.263
but apparently the energy
I burn as electricity

00:41:23.263 --> 00:41:26.767
in my home in a day could take an elevator

00:41:26.767 --> 00:41:28.440
to the top of the Empire State Building

00:41:28.440 --> 00:41:30.339
10 or 20 times.

00:41:30.339 --> 00:41:32.039
I wouldn't have thought that.

00:41:32.039 --> 00:41:35.741
Sal: That's something and it gives people

00:41:35.741 --> 00:41:37.848
a context for what a kilowatt hour is,

00:41:37.848 --> 00:41:44.763
what a calorie is, any of the above.

00:41:44.763 --> 00:41:47.692
Jon: Yeah, because we really
lack those intuitions.

00:41:47.692 --> 00:41:49.038
It kind of just struck me because I wrote

00:41:49.038 --> 00:41:53.038
about this on my blog and
I realized all my life

00:41:53.038 --> 00:41:57.269
I've thought about
electric bills as dollars,

00:41:57.269 --> 00:41:59.937
and I mentioned this was my electric bill,

00:41:59.937 --> 00:42:01.346
it was this many kilowatt hours and people

00:42:01.346 --> 00:42:04.185
wrote in from Belgium and the Netherlands

00:42:04.185 --> 00:42:06.426
and they said, "Really?"

00:42:06.426 --> 00:42:09.437
What made me surprised was that

00:42:09.437 --> 00:42:10.684
I suddenly realized, you know what?

00:42:10.684 --> 00:42:12.639
They have an intuition about what it means

00:42:12.639 --> 00:42:15.323
to be a quantity of kilowatt hours.

00:42:15.323 --> 00:42:20.912
The first order for them
isn't dollars or Euros,

00:42:20.912 --> 00:42:21.950
it's kilowatt hours.

00:42:21.950 --> 00:42:23.548
That actually means something to them

00:42:23.548 --> 00:42:24.872
in a way that it doesn't to us.

00:42:24.872 --> 00:42:26.166
I don't know, I thought that was ...

00:42:26.166 --> 00:42:28.248
Sal: You're inspiring me to do at least

00:42:28.248 --> 00:42:31.644
a couple of videos on it.

00:42:31.644 --> 00:42:34.845
Jon: Well listen, I think I should let you

00:42:34.845 --> 00:42:37.499
